headline_main: Will Women Still Want to Run?

abstract: Our secessionary mood is an emotional reaction to the election of Donald Trump and a reflection of the power of our own brand of liberalism.
snippet: Our secessionary mood is an emotional reaction to the election of Donald Trump and a reflection of the power of our own brand of liberalism.
lead_paragraph: San Francisco — THIS is going to sound very California, but here goes: I drowned my election sorrows by surfing. It didn’t help, but I was struck by something afterward. All my life, I’ve seen strangers on California beaches — bearded bodysurfers drinking local Bourbon, Republican volleyball players eating vegan energy bars — trade warm glances that say, “I salute your lifestyle choices and respect your privacy.” After the election, those furtive nods implied nausea, terror and a compassion born of confidence that others felt much the same. Within that compassion, I sensed the emergence of something new in California public life: an awareness that we Californians are bound together as one people by the shared values of our increasingly tolerant and pluralistic society.

abstract: The region, which has prospered compared with much of the rest of the country, embraced Hillary Clinton and a slew of liberal policies on Election Day.
snippet: The region, which has prospered compared with much of the rest of the country, embraced Hillary Clinton and a slew of liberal policies on Election Day.
lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — The West Coast has long prided itself as an engine for reinvention and progressive ideals, distinct from the rest of the country. But after Tuesday’s election, the states bordering the Pacific Ocean feel increasingly like an island unto its own.

abstract: Hillary Clinton’s defeat laid bare the Democratic Party’s weaknesses, and the party prepared for arguments over its future and mission.
snippet: Hillary Clinton’s defeat laid bare the Democratic Party’s weaknesses, and the party prepared for arguments over its future and mission.
lead_paragraph: When Hillary Clinton began her second bid for president, much of the Democratic Party rallied around her. Party leaders, campaign contributors and elected officials — including President Obama — sought to clear the field and ensure her an easy road to the White House.
